<h1>About Plant Track</h1>
<p>
  A dairy plant transparency lookup. Maps plant codes printed on dairy
  packaging to the plant that made the product, the brands that come out of
  that plant, and the recall history attached to it.
</p>

<h2>Data sources</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://www.fda.gov/food/milk-guidance-documents-regulatory-information/interstate-milk-shippers-list">FDA Interstate Milk Shippers List</a> — authoritative roster of Grade A plants.</li>
  <li><a href="https://open.fda.gov/apis/food/enforcement/">openFDA Food Enforcement API</a> — recall records.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.ams.usda.gov/rules-regulations/moa/dairy">USDA AMS Pool Plant Reports</a> — FMMO affiliation.</li>
  <li>Hand-curated brand-to-plant mappings, each with a source and confidence level.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What v1 covers (and what it doesn't)</h2>
<p>
  v1 lists IMS-coded Grade A fluid and cultured plants only. Packaging codes
  from other systems — FDA food facility registration numbers, USDA
  establishment numbers, state-specific codes — are not yet supported. If
  your code starts with <code>EST.</code> or is a long all-digit string, it
  probably is not an IMS code.
</p>

<h2>How confidence works</h2>
<p>
  Every brand-to-plant mapping carries a confidence level (high / medium /
  low) and a source. Recall matches carry a numeric confidence and a method
  (name, name + geography, manual). Below "high" / above 70% should be
  treated as a lead, not a fact.
</p>

<h2>Corrections</h2>
<p>
  Found a mistake? Email <code>brunndairy88@gmail.com</code> with the plant
  code or recall number and what should change. Manual overrides are
  preserved across data refreshes.
</p>

